FG-491 — Quote-Length Discipline (≤25 Words, Page:Line)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Keep quotes short, exact, pinned—or paraphrase with a pin.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Cap at ≤25 words; include page:line; use [brackets] for grammar; ellipses sparingly; no stitched quotes.
	•	📝 Assignment: Trim two quotes to ≤25 words and add page:line pins.
	•	✅ Model Response: “‘Court did not reach harm’ (Dkt 18 at 2:14–15).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Precision reads as honesty.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A scalpel trimming a quote ribbon with a tiny pin tag.

⸻

FG-492 — Relief First, Story Second (Outcome-Driven Drafting)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Draft the order text first; write only what proves it.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Two-line Primary + Fallback; every paragraph must prove a pin → remedy chain; delete the rest.
	•	📝 Assignment: Paste your two-line order at the top; cut three paragraphs that don’t serve it.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Vacate & remand 21d (a–d). Alt: clarify n.3 (‘not reached’).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Orders, not anecdotes, move courts.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: An order card at the top with arrows pulling only supporting lines.

⸻

FG-493 — Table-First Facts (Date • Event • Pin • Effect)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Facts persuade fastest in a four-column table.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Right-align dates; keep Effect ≤6 words; one pin per row; place long tables in addendum.
	•	📝 Assignment: Convert a 150-word narrative into a 10-row fact table.
	•	✅ Model Response: “07/31 — USPS receipt — Ex A:1 — timely.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Tables beat paragraphs under time pressure.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A crisp four-column grid with a bold pin column.

⸻

FG-494 — Raised/Ruled Card (Two Rows, One Ask)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Show where raised and how ruled—then your ask.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: 2-row card: Issue • Raised pin • Ruled line • Relief; neutral verbs; one-liner order.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a raised/ruled card for your top issue.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Harm — Dkt 14:3 — ‘not reached’ (Dkt 18:2) — Remand 21d.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Structure compresses advocacy.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Two-row card with a green “Relief” strip at right.

⸻

FG-495 — Posture Footnote (Triangle in One Line)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: When posture is simple, footnote it once.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: “§1291; Rule 58 08/15; NOA 08/19; Tabs 1–2”; move to first paragraph if contested.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write your posture footnote and paste it in page one.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Jurisdiction under §1291; Rule 58 08/15; NOA 08/19 (Tabs 1–2).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Comfort without clutter.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A tiny triangle symbol in the footnote area.

⸻

FG-496 — Minimal Emergency Ask (Small, Dated, Scoped)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Emergencies win on small + dated + scoped.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Ask for 72h admin stay, limit to one paragraph, show deadline and pin, add a status line.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 5-line emergency ask with one pin and one date.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Stay ¶3 for 72h; print 09/05 12:00 (Vendor Decl ¶7); status 48h; sunset auto.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: The smaller the door, the faster it opens.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A pause badge over a single bracketed paragraph.

⸻

FG-497 — Mislink/Metadata Fix (Replace • Suppress • Hash)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Correct intake errors with equivalence + new hash—not re-filing.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Notice: before/after title, equivalence line (“no argument change”), new SHA-256, ask to suppress prior link; add a cite-sub table if pages moved.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 7-line mislink/metadata correction notice.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Correct ‘Letter’ → ‘Motion to Clarify’; no argument change; new SHA-256 41be22…; suppress prior link.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Hygiene preserves momentum.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A label peeled off and a new clean label snapped on.

⸻

FG-498 — One-Pin Paragraphs (Anchor First)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Start paragraphs with a pin clause; feelings come last.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Topic sentence = Pin → claim; delete adverbs; move detail to crosswalk/appendix.
	•	📝 Assignment: Rewrite three paragraphs to start with pins.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Dkt 18 at 2 shows harm not reached; remand required.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Anchors make skim-reading decisive.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A paragraph with its first words underlined as a pin.

⸻

FG-499 — Micro-Errata (Fix the Line, Keep the Clock)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Correct a single line without resetting schedules.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Title “Micro-Errata (No Schedule Change)”; table: Page • Before → After • Reason; attach corrected page; new hash line.
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft a 4-row micro-errata for your brief.
	•	✅ Model Response: “p.12 n.3 ‘reached’ → ‘not reached’; reason: transcription; SHA-256 ….”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Small fixes get quick yeses.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A tiny redline bubble next to a calendar stamped “unchanged.”

⸻

FG-500 — Close With a Card (Pins → Order → Scope)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: End every filing with a card: two pins, two-line order, scope.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Paste the card at the end of your conclusion; mirror in OA notes; keep neutral; no adjectives.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build your end-card and paste it into your draft today.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Pins: Dkt 18:2; Tab 3 p.2. Relief: remand 21d (a–d). Scope: ¶3 parties only; status 14d.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Cards are signable endings.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small card anchored to the last page with a signature strip.